# 🧠 Makefile Execution — Story Mode (How `make` thinks)

---

## 🎬 The Story Begins

You type:

```bash
make
```

👉 The program (make) starts thinking like this:

---

## 🧩 Step 1 — Start from `all`

```make
all: $(NAME)
```

### 🧠 Story

👉 “My first task is `all`
👉 To complete `all`, I need: `libft.a`”

---

## 🧩 Step 2 — Do I have `libft.a`?

```make
$(NAME): $(OBJS)
	ar rcs $(NAME) $(OBJS)
```

### 🧠 Story

👉 “Do I already have `libft.a`?”

* ✔ YES and up-to-date → **do nothing ✅**
* ❌ NO → “I must build it!”

👉 “To build `libft.a`, I need `.o` files”

---

## 🧩 Step 3 — Do I have `.o` files?

```make
OBJS = $(SRCS:.c=.o)
```

### 🧠 Story

👉 “Do I have all `.o` files?”

* ✔ YES and up-to-date → “Good, I can archive them”
* ❌ NO → “I must create them”

---

## 🧩 Step 4 — Build `.o` from `.c`

```make
%.o: %.c
	$(CC) $(CFLAGS) -c $< -o $@
```

### 🧠 Story

👉 “To build `.o`, I need `.c`”

👉 “Let me compile each file”

```bash
cc -Wall -Wextra -Werror -c file.c -o file.o
```

---

## 🧩 Step 5 — Create the library

```make
ar rcs $(NAME) $(OBJS)
```

### 🧠 Story

👉 “Now I have all `.o` files”

👉 “I will pack them into one file”

```bash
ar rcs libft.a file1.o file2.o ...
```

👉 🎉 `libft.a` created!

---

# 🔁 Full Story Summary

👉 Make thinks like this:

```text
Do I need libft.a?
 ├── YES → do nothing
 └── NO
      ↓
Do I have .o files?
 ├── YES → archive them → libft.a
 └── NO
      ↓
Compile .c → .o
      ↓
Archive → libft.a
```

---

# 📊 Diagram (Visual Flow)

```text
          make
            ↓
         [all]
            ↓
      need libft.a?
        /       \
     yes         no
     ↓           ↓
   STOP      need .o files?
                /       \
             yes         no
             ↓           ↓
        ar rcs .a     compile .c → .o
             ↓           ↓
         libft.a ←───────┘
```

---

# 🧠 Memory Trick (Never Forget)

👉 **“make builds only what’s missing”**

👉 Chain:

```text
.c → .o → .a
```

---

# 🎯 Final Mental Image

👉 Make is like a **lazy worker**:

* “If everything is ready → I do nothing 😎”
* “If something is missing → I build only that part 🔧”

---

Perfect 🔥 let’s continue the same **story style** for `clean`, `fclean`, `re`.

---

# 🧹 Makefile — Cleaning Rules (Story Mode)

---

## 🎬 You type:

```bash
make clean
```

---

## 🧩 Rule

```make
clean:
	rm -f $(OBJS)
```

### 🧠 Story

👉 Make says:

> “You don’t want compiled parts anymore?
> Fine… I will delete all `.o` files”

👉 It does:

```bash
rm -f file1.o file2.o ...
```

---

### 🎯 Result

```text
.c files  → still exist ✔
.o files  → deleted ❌
libft.a   → still exists ✔
```

---

## 🧠 Memory

👉 *clean = remove intermediate files*

---

# 💣 `fclean` — Full Clean

---

## 🎬 You type:

```bash
make fclean
```

---

## 🧩 Rule

```make
fclean: clean
	rm -f $(NAME)
```

---

### 🧠 Story

👉 Make says:

> “First, I will do `clean`
> Then I will also delete the final product”

---

### Step-by-step:

1. Run `clean`

```bash
rm -f *.o
```

2. Then:

```bash
rm -f libft.a
```

---

### 🎯 Result

```text
.c files  → still exist ✔
.o files  → deleted ❌
libft.a   → deleted ❌
```

---

## 🧠 Memory

👉 *fclean = full clean (everything except source)*

---

# 🔄 `re` — Rebuild Everything

---

## 🎬 You type:

```bash
make re
```

---

## 🧩 Rule

```make
re: fclean all
```

---

### 🧠 Story

👉 Make says:

> “Destroy everything… then rebuild from scratch”

---

### Step-by-step:

1. Run `fclean`

```bash
rm -f *.o
rm -f libft.a
```

2. Then run `all`

```bash
make
```

👉 which triggers full build again

---

### 🎯 Result

```text
fresh compilation ✔
fresh libft.a ✔
```

---

## 🧠 Memory

👉 *re = reset + rebuild*

---

# 📊 Full Cleaning Flow Diagram

```text
make clean
    ↓
delete .o only

make fclean
    ↓
delete .o
    ↓
delete libft.a

make re
    ↓
fclean
    ↓
all
    ↓
rebuild everything
```

---

# 🧠 Final Mental Model

👉 `clean` → clean workspace
👉 `fclean` → wipe everything
👉 `re` → restart from zero

---

# 🎯 One-Line Memory

```text
clean  = remove parts
fclean = remove parts + product
re     = rebuild everything
```

---

